</md></sn><sn><md>### Measuring Atmospheric Pressure

#### Formula

$$
P = \frac{F}{A}
$$


### Approximation using Earthâ€™s parameters

Instead of using $\rho$ and $h$, we can derive pressure from the **weight of the atmosphere per unit area**:

As $F = mg$ ,

$$
P = \frac{M_{\text{atm}} \, g}{A_{\oplus}}
$$

+++ where

* $M_{\text{atm}}$ = total mass of Earthâ€™s atmosphere â‰ˆ $5.15 \times 10^{18}\ \text{kg}$
* $g$ = 9.80665 m/sÂ²
* $A_{\oplus}$ = surface area of Earth = $4 \pi R^2$, with Earthâ€™s mean radius $R \approx 6.371 \times 10^6\ \text{m}$
+++

### Calculation

1. **Earthâ€™s surface area**

$$
A_{\oplus} = 4 \pi (6.371 \times 10^6)^2 \approx 5.10 \times 10^{14}\ \text{m}^2
$$

2. **Total weight of atmosphere**

$$
W = M_{\text{atm}} g = (5.15 \times 10^{18})(9.80665) \approx 5.05 \times 10^{19}\ \text{N}
$$

3. **Pressure**

$$
P = \frac{W}{A_{\oplus}} = \frac{5.05 \times 10^{19}}{5.10 \times 10^{14}}
\approx 9.91 \times 10^4\ \text{Pa}
$$

#### Result

$$
P \approx 1.01 \times 10^5\ \text{Pa} = 101\ \text{kPa} \approx 1\ \text{atm}
$$

At sea-level the mass of air on per `unit square meter` surface area is about `10000 kg` per square meter,that is ==1kg per square centimeter==.
